Tutorial 3 - Fuel Up Your API Development with Hono and Deno

7 steps

In this tutorial, you will continue building an API that allows users to create, replace, update and delete data using Hono and Deno. By going through this quest, you will gain one example application of how to build an API for different domains. You will also learn how to create protected routes for certain API endpoints that require authentication and authorisation.

Let's continue and finish up your first API development journey with Hono and Deno.

As this is a continuation of Tutorial 1 and Tutorial 2, ensure you have finished those two tutorials first.

Prerequisites

  • Required to have finished Tutorial 1.
  • Required to have finished Tutorial 2.
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript.
  • A working development environment of VSCode.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Required to have finished Tutorial 1.
  • Required to have finished Tutorial 2.
  • Familiarity with Javascript and Typescript.
  • A working development environment of VSCode.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Build APIs using Hono and Deno.
  • Create protected routes with Hono.
  • Include tests for your backend.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 7

  • Step 1: Cryptographic Logic

    In this step, you have to install three additional dependencies. Run the following command.

    deno add 'jsr:@std/crypto' 'jsr:@std/encoding' 'jsr:@zaubrik/djwt' 'npm:zod@3.23.8'

    The following dependencies are used to write cryptographic logic for your backend for protecting API endpoints or routes.

    The @std/crypto has underlying WebCrypto APIs, which are Web Standards, and @std/encoding which has encoder and decoder functions to transform bytes to unicode strings, vice versa.

    The last dependency, djwt, is a package that allows us to generate JSON Web Tokens (JWT). You will be using a web standard called SubtleCrypto to perform signing and verifying JWT.

    Secret Key Generator

    At the root directory of your project, create a file called generateToken.ts. Write the following code to the new file.

    import { crypto } from "@std/crypto";
import { encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";

const apiKey = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(16));
console.log(`GENERATED API_KEY:\`${encodeBase64(apiKey)}\``);
    TypeScript

    This serves as the script to generate your API_KEY or your secret key. You will be using this to generate hashed passwords.

    To generate the secret key, run the following command.

    deno run generateToken.ts

    Copy the value between the backticks (`). For example, if you get `IamAnAPIKey`, then copy only IamAnApiKey. Create a new file called .env at the root directory of your project. Write this to your new .env file.

    API_KEY="YourAPIKey"
    Plain text

    where YourAPIKey is your generated API key or token. Ensure that it's within the double quotes.

    Note that you can even skip generating the API_KEY. Future code in this tutorial will still work. The point of this exercise is to let you know that there are ways to generate your own cryptographically secure token for secret keys and they are very important to prevent tampered passwords.

    JWT Logic

    Hono already has a built-in middleware for generating JWT. But you are not going to use it for this tutorial. It's better to understand the underlying implementation first before heading towards using the easiest but obscured method.

    At the root directory of your project, create a new directory called auth. Head to the auth directory and create a new file called jwt.ts. Open the file and write the following code.

    import { create, getNumericDate, verify } from "@zaubrik/djwt";
import { PersonalDetail } from "../types/inferred.ts";

/**
 * Our JWT key to be used to generate the signature.
 */
const key = await crypto.subtle.generateKey(
  { name: "HMAC", hash: "SHA-512" },
  false,
  ["sign", "verify"],
);

/**
 * Generates a Json Web Token (JWT) for user login authentication.
 * This JWT is used throughout a user's session until it expires.
 * @param payload User data such as email and id
 * @param origin domain name of source origin
 * @returns `Promise<string|undefined>`
 */
const generateJwt = async (
  payload: PersonalDetail | undefined,
  origin: string,
) => {
  if (!payload) return payload;

  /**
   * **N**ot **B**e**F**ore
   */
  const nbf = new Date();
  nbf.setDate(nbf.getDate() + 365);

  const jwt = await create({
    alg: "HS512",
    type: "JWT",
  }, {
    exp: getNumericDate(nbf),
    aud: origin,
    email: payload.email,
  }, key);

  return { jwt, nbf };
};

/**
 * Verifies the signature of the JWT
 * @param jwt The JWT signature
 * @returns `string` value which is the email.
 */
const verifyJwt = async (jwt: string) => {
  const payload: { email: string } = await verify(
    jwt,
    key,
  );

  return payload;
};

export { generateJwt, verifyJwt };
    TypeScript

    You might have noticed that there is a new type called PersonalDetail that is not implemented yet. The great thing about zod is that it can perform type inference on zod schemas.

    Head back to the root directory of your project and create a directory called types. Head to the types directory and create a new file called inferred.ts. Open the new file and write the following code.

    import AnimalSchema from "../mock/animal.schema.ts";
import PersonalDetailSchema from "../mock/personal-details.schema.ts";
import { z } from "zod";

export type PersonalDetail = z.infer<typeof PersonalDetailSchema>;
export type Animal = z.infer<typeof AnimalSchema>;
    TypeScript

    With the new code, you don't have to manually write the types to match the "shape" of the data structures. You can just use the .infer method from zod.

    Password Hashing Logic

    At the root directory of your project, add the following dependencies by running the following command.

    deno add 'jsr:@std/dotenv/load' 'jsr:@denosaurs/argontwo'

    This will install https://jsr.io/@std/dotenv and also generate your API key.

    This also installs argontwo, a package that contains crypto logic based on the battle-tested argon2 password hashing algorithm. It also has a feature to include a salt which is a randomised set of characters grouped in varied lengths. A salt is needed to decrease the chances of hash collisions.

    A hash collision is when two or more sets of data return the same hash. But no two people should have the same hash even if they have the same password through this method called salting.

    Head to the auth directory and create a new file called pwd.ts. Open the file and write the following code.

    import { decodeBase64, encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";
import { type Argon2Params, hash } from "@denosaurs/argontwo";
import "@std/dotenv/load";

const TOKEN = decodeBase64(Deno.env.get("API_KEY") ?? "");
const encoder = new TextEncoder();

export const argon2Verify = (
  password: string,
  salt: string,
  originalHash: string,
): boolean => {
  const encodedPassword = encoder.encode(password);
  const encodedSalt = encoder.encode(salt);
  const params: Argon2Params = {
    algorithm: "Argon2id",
    secret: TOKEN,
    version: 0x13,
  };
  const ret =
    encodeBase64(hash(encodedPassword, encodedSalt, params)) === originalHash;
  return ret;
};

export const argon2Hasher = (password: string, salt: string): ArrayBuffer => {
  const encodedPassword = encoder.encode(password);
  const encodedSalt = encoder.encode(salt);
  const params: Argon2Params = {
    algorithm: "Argon2id",
    secret: TOKEN,
    version: 0x13,
  };
  return hash(encodedPassword, encodedSalt, params);
};
    TypeScript

    You have written two important functions here. Most argon2 interfacing libraries have their own verify function built-in. But it's just a wrapper of the hash function of argon2.

    With this implementation, you learn that to verify a password is to compare hashes between the original hash and the regenerated hash using the password and original salt value.

    The functions argon2Verify and argon2Hasher use a variant of argon2 called argon2id. It is a hybrid combination of the two other variants, argon2i and argon2d. This campaign won't go too deep about the intricacies of argon2 but it's the recommended password hashing algorithm according to OWASP recommendations.

  • Step 2: Auto Populate Multiple Databases For Mock Tests

    Ensure that you close the terminal that is running the deno task serve command. This allows you to close and quit the HTTP server since it is required in this step.

    Before protecting our API endpoints, let's write some tests. But first, you have to write a way to populate a database containing pet or animal data, and user personal details data. The populated data is not actual real data but is only used for mocking and testing.

    At the root directory of the project, run the following command.

    deno add 'jsr:@db/sqlite' 'jsr:@std/encoding'

    Head to the mock directory. Create a new directory called database. Head to database directory.

    Create a file called mod.ts. Write the following code to mod.ts.

    import animalDb from "./animal.db.ts";
import personalDetailsDb from "./personal-details.db.ts";

export { animalDb, personalDetailsDb };
    TypeScript

    Create a file called animal.db.ts. Write the following code to animal.db.ts.

export const create_animal_table_command = `

                owner TEXT NOT NULL,
                animal TEXT NOT NULL

`;

    TypeScript

    Create a file called personal-details.db.ts. Write the following code to personal-details.db.ts.

    import { Database } from "@db/sqlite";
const personalDetailsDb = new Database("./mock/database/people.db");

export const create_people_table_command = `
        CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS people(
                id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,

    TypeScript

    You might have wondered why you are putting this inside the mock directory. This indicates that our API backend is still not ready for production and it's still under development and testing. Ensure sensible naming schemes for directories so that it communicates well the purpose of your codebase.

    Once thoroughly tested, one can then promote and update the codebase to production.

    Let's proceed in adding the necessary code to auto generate and populate mock/fake data to SQLite databases.

    Head back to the mock directory. Create a file called generateMockDatabase.ts. Write the following code to generateMockDatabase.ts.

    import { create_people_table_command } from "./database/personal-details.db.ts";
import { create_animal_table_command } from "./database/animal.db.ts";
import { factoryAnimals, factoryPeople } from "./factory.ts";
import { argon2Hasher } from "../auth/pwd.ts";
import { encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";
import { Database } from "@db/sqlite";

const generateMockAnimalDataForDb = (db: Database) => {
  factoryAnimals.forEach((animal) => {
    const stmt = db.prepare(
      "INSERT INTO pets(id, owner, animal) VALUES (?, ?, ?);",
    );
    stmt.run(
      animal.id,
      animal.owner,
      animal.animal,
    );
  });
};

const generateMockPersonalDataForDb = (db: Database) => {
  factoryPeople.forEach((person) => {
    const randSalt = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(32));
    const salt = encodeBase64(randSalt);
    const hashedPassword = encodeBase64(argon2Hasher(person.password, salt));
    const stmt = db.prepare(
      "INSERT INTO people(id, firstName, lastName, email, password, salt) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?);",
    );
    stmt.run(
      person.id,
      person.firstName,
      person.lastName,
      person.email,
      hashedPassword,
      salt,
    );
  });
};

export const generateMockDataForDb = (
  personalDetailsMockDbPath: string,
  animalMockDbPath: string,
) => {
  //   console.log("This will delete your previous generated database");
  try {
    Deno.removeSync(personalDetailsMockDbPath);
    Deno.removeSync(animalMockDbPath);
  } catch (_err) {
    // console.warn(
    //   `Warning: Deleting operation failed. Got ${err}. This error is harmless and just means the files do not exist.`,
    // );
  }
  const personalDetailsMockDb = new Database(personalDetailsMockDbPath);
  const animalMockDb = new Database(animalMockDbPath);

  personalDetailsMockDb.exec(create_people_table_command);
  generateMockPersonalDataForDb(personalDetailsMockDb);

  animalMockDb.exec(create_animal_table_command);
  generateMockAnimalDataForDb(animalMockDb);
  return {
    personalDetailsMockDb,
    animalMockDb,
  };
};
    TypeScript

    This code will be used for testing purposes in the next step.

  • Step 3: Adding Tests

    Run the following command.

    deno add 'jsr:@std/assert'

    @std/assert is part of the standard library, useful for testing.

    You will add tests for the schemas. At the root of the directory, head to the mock directory. Create a file called personal-details.schema_test.ts. Write the following code to personal-details.schema_test.ts.

    import { assert } from "@std/assert";

// Actually, this is an optional test since Zod follows a functional programming concept "Parse, don't validate."
// See https://lexi-lambda.github.io/blog/2019/11/05/parse-don-t-validate/
Deno.test("Personal details matches Zod object schema `PersonalDetailSchema`.", () => {
  factoryPeople.forEach((person) => {
    assert(
      PersonalDetailSchema.safeParse({
        id: person.id,
        firstName: person.firstName,
        lastName: person.lastName,
        email: person.email,
        password: person.password,
      }).success,
    );
  });
});
    TypeScript

    Next, create a file called animal.schema_test.ts. Write the following code to animal.schema_test.ts.

    import { assert } from "@std/assert";

Deno.test("Animal or pet details matches Zod object schema `AnimalSchema`.", () => {

    TypeScript

    You will see the same comment there about "Parse, don't validate". Although zod allows the avoidance of further testing because of its "parse, don't validate" approach, you can always try to test your inputs and ensure that they match the zod schemas you defined.

    Lastly, create a file called mock_test.ts. Write the following code to mock_test.ts.

    import { argon2Verify } from "../auth/pwd.ts";
import { generateMockDataForDb } from "./generateMockDatabase.ts";
import { factoryPeople } from "./factory.ts";
import { assert } from "@std/assert";
import { PersonalDetailWithSalt } from "../types/common.ts";

Deno.test("All password hashes are verified with their respective salt.", () => {
  const personalDetailsMockDbPath = "./mock/database/people-mock.db";
  const animalMockDbPath = "./mock/database/pets-mock.db";
  const { personalDetailsMockDb } = generateMockDataForDb(
    personalDetailsMockDbPath,
    animalMockDbPath,
  );
  factoryPeople.forEach((person) => {
    const stmt = personalDetailsMockDb.prepare(
      `
					SELECT * FROM people WHERE email = '${person.email}';
					`,
    );
    const row = stmt.get<PersonalDetailWithSalt>();
    assert(row !== undefined);
    // NOTE: row.password refers to an already hashed password.
    assert(argon2Verify(person.password, row.salt, row.password));
  });
});
    TypeScript

    Here, you have tested that all password hashes generated and stored in the database are verified. This ensures that password hashes from the database are correct.

    Head to the root directory of your project. Head to the types directory. Create a new file called common.ts. Write the following code to common.ts.

    import { PersonalDetail } from "./inferred.ts";

export interface PersonalDetailWithSalt extends PersonalDetail {
  salt: string;
}
    TypeScript

    This contains code that extends the type PersonalDetail to match the shape of the personal detail data stored in the SQLite database.

    Save all files. Run the following command to run the tests.

    It should show a similar output like the screenshot below.

  • Step 4: Adding checkAuth function

    Your goal in this project is to protect API endpoints for any unauthorised modification. This means any method that can modify a resource e.g. PUT, POST, DELETE, and PATCH. For now, you will only focus on methods PUT and DELETE.

    Head to the root directory of your project. Head to the auth directory. Create a new file called checkAuth.ts. Write the following code to checkAuth.ts.

    import { verifyJwt } from "./jwt.ts";
import { getCookie } from "@hono/hono/cookie";
import type { Context, Next } from "@hono/hono";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";

/**
Checks if user is authenticated by checking the request cookie
and the Authorization header. Then the JWT tokens are pulled
from both cookie and header and then compared if it matches.

If they don't match, then function just early returns with
null/undefined.
 */
const checkAuth = async (
  ctx: Context,
  next: Next,
) => {
  const method = ctx.req.method;
  if (
    (method === "PUT" || method === "DELETE")
  ) {
    const jwtFromCookie = getCookie(ctx, "jwt");
    console.log(jwtFromCookie);
    let jwtSignature: string = "";

    const authHeader = ctx.req.header("Authorization");
    if (!authHeader) {
      throw new HTTPException(403, {
        message: "You are not allowed to modify this resource.",
      });
    }
    const [, jwtSig] = authHeader.split(" ");
    console.log(jwtSig);
    if (!jwtSig.trim() || !jwtFromCookie) {
      throw new HTTPException(403, {
        message: "You are not allowed to modify this resource.",
      });
    }
    jwtSignature = jwtSig;
    if (
      (jwtFromCookie === jwtSignature)
    ) {
      const jwtCookieValue = await verifyJwt(jwtFromCookie);
      const jwtAuthValue = await verifyJwt(jwtSig);
      const verified = jwtAuthValue.email === jwtCookieValue.email;
      console.log("Is verified?", verified);
      if (!verified) {
        throw new HTTPException(403, {
          message: "You are not allowed to modify this resource.",
        });
      } else {
        return await next();
      }
    }
    throw new HTTPException(403, {
      message: "You are not allowed to modify this resource.",
    });
  }
  await next();
};

export default checkAuth;
    TypeScript

    The code will use the verifyJwt function and verifies the JSON Web Token signature string if it can be verified. This JWT signature should be set for both cookie and authorization header. If it matches, the code will proceed to the desired API endpoint with the method intended for modifying a resource.

    One can simply add this line of code before all the declared API endpoints or routes. Simply just head to the root directory of your project and replace all contents of main.ts with the following code.

    import { Hono } from "@hono/hono";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";
import { factoryPeople } from "./mock/factory.ts";
import { animalDb, personalDetailsDb } from "./mock/database/mod.ts";
import { PersonalDetail } from "./types/inferred.ts";
import { create_animal_table_command } from "./mock/database/animal.db.ts";
import { create_people_table_command } from "./mock/database/personal-details.db.ts";
import { Animal } from "./types/inferred.ts";
import checkAuth from "./auth/checkAuth.ts";
import { PersonalDetailWithSalt } from "./types/common.ts";

if (animalDb.open) {
  animalDb.exec(create_animal_table_command);
}

if (personalDetailsDb.open) {
  personalDetailsDb.exec(create_people_table_command);
}

const animals = new Hono().basePath("/animals");
const people = new Hono().basePath("/people");
const app = new Hono().basePath("/api");

animals.use(checkAuth);
people.use(checkAuth);

animals.get("/", (c) => {
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets;");
  const rows = stmt.all<Animal>();
  return c.json(rows);
}).put(async (c) => {
  const randUUID = crypto.randomUUID();
  const userInput = await c.req.json<{ animal: string; owner: string }>();
  const animal: Animal = {
    animal: userInput.animal,
    owner: userInput.owner,
    id: randUUID,
  };
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare(
    "INSERT INTO pets(id, owner, animal) VALUES (?, ?, ?);",
  );
  const changes = stmt.run(
    animal.id,
    animal.owner,
    animal.animal,
  );
  if (changes > 0) {
    return c.json(animal);
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(500, {
      message: "Failed to write animal data to database.",
    });
  }
});

animals.get("/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets WHERE id = ?;");
  const row = stmt.get<Animal>(id);
  if (!row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(row);
}).put(async (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const userInput = await c.req.json<{
    owner: string;
  }>();
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets WHERE id = ?;");
  const row = stmt.get<Animal>(id);
  if (!row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  const stmt2 = animalDb.prepare("UPDATE pets SET owner = ? WHERE id = ?;");
  const changes = stmt2.run(userInput.owner, id);
  if (changes > 0) {
    const stmt3 = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets WHERE id = ?;");
    const newRow = stmt3.get<Animal>(id);
    if (!newRow) {
      throw new HTTPException(404, {
        message: "ID not found.",
      });
    }
    return c.json(newRow);
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(500, {
      message: "Failed to write animal data to database.",
    });
  }
});

app.route("/", animals);

people.get("/", (c) => {
  return c.json(factoryPeople);
});

people.get("/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const personalDetail = factoryPeople.find((el) =>
    el.id === Number.parseInt(id)
  );
  if (!personalDetail) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(personalDetail);
});

app.route("/", people);
if (import.meta.main) {
  Deno.serve({ hostname: "127.0.0.1", port: 5555 }, app.fetch);
}
    TypeScript

    However, you still need to give access to some users to modify a resource. This will be done in the next step.

  • Step 5: Adding Login and Register Middleware

    Since you need to protect some API endpoints, you have to create a new API endpoint for registering a user and logging-in of a user with modification privileges or access.

    These users can be referred to as admins since they are given modification access to specific API endpoints. Specifically, API endpoints that modify a resource i.e. pet owner details, and personal details.

    Head to the root directory of your project. Create a new directory called middleware. Head to the middleware directory. Create two files, login.ts and register.ts.

    Write the following code to register.ts.

    import { Context } from "@hono/hono";
import { argon2Hasher } from "../auth/pwd.ts";
import type { BlankEnv, BlankInput } from "@hono/hono/types";
import { personalDetailsDb } from "../mock/database/mod.ts";
import { PersonalDetailWithSalt } from "../types/common.ts";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";
import { encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";

const registerUser = async (
  c: Context<BlankEnv, "/auth/admin/register", BlankInput>,
) => {
  const userInput = await c.req.json<
    { firstName: string; lastName: string; email: string; password: string }
  >();
  const stmt1 = personalDetailsDb.prepare(
    "SELECT * FROM people WHERE email = ?",
  );
  const row = stmt1.get<PersonalDetailWithSalt>(userInput.email);
  if (row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, { message: "User already exists." });
  }
  const randSalt = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(32));
  const salt = encodeBase64(randSalt);
  const hashedPassword = encodeBase64(argon2Hasher(userInput.password, salt));
  const stmt2 = personalDetailsDb.prepare(
    "INSERT INTO people(firstName, lastName, email, password, salt) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?);",
  );
  const changes = stmt2.run(
    userInput.firstName,
    userInput.lastName,
    userInput.email,
    hashedPassword,
    salt,
  );
  if (changes > 0) {
    return c.json(userInput);
  }
  throw new HTTPException(503, { message: "Server error." });
};

export default registerUser;
    TypeScript

    However, your route's common basePath is /api. Specifically, your app variable needs to change back to / which is the default. To do this, your main.ts from the root directory of the project will have changed the following variables to the code below. Don't write that yet as this is only mentioned for the purpose that you will have to edit again the whole code of main.ts later.

    const animals = new Hono().basePath("/api/animals");
const people = new Hono().basePath("/api/people");
const app = new Hono();
    TypeScript

    Next, write the following code to login.ts.

    import { Context } from "@hono/hono";
import { argon2Verify } from "../auth/pwd.ts";
import type { BlankEnv, BlankInput } from "@hono/hono/types";
import { personalDetailsDb } from "../mock/database/mod.ts";
import { PersonalDetail } from "../types/inferred.ts";
import { PersonalDetailWithSalt } from "../types/common.ts";
import { HTTPException } from "@hono/hono/http-exception";
import { generateJwt } from "../auth/jwt.ts";
import { setCookie } from "@hono/hono/cookie";

const loginUser = async (
  c: Context<BlankEnv, "/auth/admin/login", BlankInput>,
) => {
  const userInput = await c.req.json<{ email: string; password: string }>();
  const stmt1 = personalDetailsDb.prepare(
    "SELECT * FROM people WHERE email = ?",
  );
  const row = stmt1.get<PersonalDetailWithSalt>(userInput.email);
  if (!row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, { message: "User does not exist." });
  }
  const verified = argon2Verify(userInput.password, row.salt, row.password);
  if (verified) {
    const personalDetail: PersonalDetail = {
      id: row.id,
      firstName: row.firstName,
      lastName: row.lastName,
      email: row.email,
      password: userInput.password,
    };
    const jwtData = await generateJwt(personalDetail, c.req.url);
    if (!jwtData) {
      throw new HTTPException(503, { message: "Server Error." });
    }
    setCookie(c, "jwt", jwtData.jwt, {
      expires: new Date(jwtData.nbf),
      secure: false,
      sameSite: "Lax",
      path: "/",
      httpOnly: true,
    });
    return c.text("User has logged in");
  }
  throw new HTTPException(403, { message: "Invalid credentials." });
};

export default loginUser;
    TypeScript

    Finally, head back to the root directory of your project. Replace all the content of main.ts with the following code.

    import { Hono } from "@hono/hono";

const admin = new Hono().basePath("/auth/admin");
const animals = new Hono().basePath("/api/animals");
const people = new Hono().basePath("/api/people");
const app = new Hono();

admin.post("/register", registerUser);
admin.post("/login", loginUser);
app.route("/", admin);

people.use(checkAuth);

animals.get("/", (c) => {
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets;");
  const rows = stmt.all<Animal>();
  return c.json(rows);
}).put(async (c) => {
  const randUUID = crypto.randomUUID();
  const userInput = await c.req.json<{ animal: string; owner: string }>();
  const animal: Animal = {
    animal: userInput.animal,
    owner: userInput.owner,
    id: randUUID,
  };
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare(
    "INSERT INTO pets(id, owner, animal) VALUES (?, ?, ?);",
  );
  const changes = stmt.run(
    animal.id,
    animal.owner,
    animal.animal,
  );
  if (changes > 0) {
    return c.json(animal);
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(500, {
      message: "Failed to write animal data to database.",
    });
  }
});

animals.get("/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets WHERE id = ?;");
  const row = stmt.get<Animal>(id);
  if (!row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(row);
}).put(async (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const userInput = await c.req.json<{
    owner: string;
  }>();
  const stmt = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets WHERE id = ?;");
  const row = stmt.get<Animal>(id);
  if (!row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  const stmt2 = animalDb.prepare("UPDATE pets SET owner = ? WHERE id = ?;");
  const changes = stmt2.run(userInput.owner, id);
  if (changes > 0) {
    const stmt3 = animalDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM pets WHERE id = ?;");
    const newRow = stmt3.get<Animal>(id);
    if (!newRow) {
      throw new HTTPException(404, {
        message: "ID not found.",
      });
    }
    return c.json(newRow);
  } else {
    throw new HTTPException(500, {
      message: "Failed to write animal data to database.",
    });
  }
});

app.route("/", animals);

people.get("/", (c) => {
  return c.json(factoryPeople);
});

people.get("/:id", (c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const personalDetail = factoryPeople.find((el) =>
    el.id === Number.parseInt(id)
  );
  if (!personalDetail) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, {
      message: "ID not found.",
    });
  }
  return c.json(personalDetail);
}).delete((c) => {
  const { id } = c.req.param();
  const stmt = personalDetailsDb.prepare("SELECT * FROM people WHERE id = ?;");
  const row = stmt.get<PersonalDetailWithSalt>(id);
  if (!row) {
    throw new HTTPException(404, { message: "User not found." });
  }
  const deleteOperation = personalDetailsDb.prepare(
    "DELETE FROM people WHERE id = ?;",
  );
  const changes = deleteOperation.run(id);
  if (changes > 0) {
    return c.text(
      `User with email "${row.email}" has been deleted in the database.`,
    );
  }
  throw new HTTPException(503, {
    message: "Server error. Unable to delete user in the database.",
  });
});

app.route("/", people);
